  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A dibber makes planting holes in prepared soil: push the pointed tip in, lever sideways to open the hole to the right size, lower the plant, close the soil. The "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "riven",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "riven"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "billet",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "billet"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " of "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "green",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "green-wood"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " birch is shaped on the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "shaving horse",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "shaving-horse"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " with a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "drawknife",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "drawknife"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Birch is one of the most common UK coppice and windfall species; a straight birch pole from a hedgerow provides ideal dibber blanks. This is the first shaving-horse project: a single piece, no joints, one taper from handle to tip."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "infoPanel",
        "attrs": {
          "tone": "default",
          "title": "Before you start cutting"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "bulletList",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Grip: four-finger grip on the work; thumb-push grip on the knife. Never make a cut whose blade-path can reach a body part."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Cut direction: push cuts and thumb-pivot cuts are the default. Pull cuts only with the work braced against the chest and the blade-arc unable to reach anything vital."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Sharpening: a dull tool slips. Strop every fifteen minutes of carving, hone weekly, oilstone monthly."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "First aid: keep a styptic pencil, gauze, and a clean dressing within reach. A cut that shows fat or will not close with pressure goes to A&E, not a plaster."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              },
              {
                "type": "listItem",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "paragraph",
                    "content": [
                      {
                        "type": "text",
                        "text": "Workspace: stable seat, good light, no children or pets within arm-and-blade reach."
                      }
                    ]
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The wood"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A straight riven birch billet: 50 cm long, 4 cm across. The billet should be taken from close-grained young birch, no more than 6 cm in diameter at the source. Hazel is a good substitute; ash works but is denser and harder on the drawknife edge."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tools"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A straight "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "drawknife",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "drawknife"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "; a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "shaving horse",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termSlug": "shaving-horse"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "; an optional sloyd knife for the pointed tip; a leather strop."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Clamp the billet in the shaving horse with the butt end in the jaw. Work the drawknife from the shoulder toward the butt, taking the corners off the square or polygonal billet to form a rough octagon in cross-section. Check the diameter with calipers: target 28 mm."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Continue to round the cross-section, working around the perimeter in overlapping passes. The finished handle section (top 35 cm) should be 26 mm in diameter."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Re-clamp with the tip end in the jaw. Work the taper on the bottom 15 cm from 26 mm at the shoulder down to a 10 mm diameter point. Use shorter strokes as the taper narrows; long strokes on a thin taper will flex the work."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Finish the very tip to a rounded point with "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "push cuts",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "termSlug": "push-cut"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " on the sloyd knife if available, or the drawknife corner for the final 5 cm. The tip does not need to be sharp; a blunt point of 8 mm diameter opens a planting hole without breaking roots."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Leave to dry for 3 weeks before use. The birch will harden and stiffen as it seasons."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Finishing"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sand through 120 grit along the grain. Apply raw linseed oil; let soak for 30 minutes, wipe off the surplus. A garden tool has no food-contact requirement; the oil is a weathering barrier only."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Variations"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Shorter dibber for pots: 25 cm long, 20 mm diameter, 6 mm pointed tip for individual seed cells."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Graduated markings: cut shallow V-grooves at 5 cm intervals along the lower half to gauge planting depth."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Hazel instead of birch: slightly softer, more common as a managed hedgerow species."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "heading": "What can go wrong",
          "intro": "Common problems and their fixes.",
          "items": [
            {
              "symptom": "Dibber bends to one side when pushed into soil",
              "cause": "Handle not round in cross-section; one side thicker",
              "fix": "Check the handle cross-section with calipers at several points before drying. A consistent 26 mm diameter all round prevents bending."
            },
            {
              "symptom": "Drawknife tears on the tip section",
              "cause": "Taper section too thin to resist the downward pressure of the drawknife",
              "fix": "Switch to the sloyd knife for the final 10 cm of the taper. The knife gives more control on narrow cross-sections."
            },
            {
              "symptom": "Tip splits during drying",
              "cause": "Tip thinned too much while still green",
              "fix": "Leave the tip at 10 mm diameter in the green state. Final thinning can be done after drying."
            }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}